00:00:06,390 --> 00:00:10,570
In this lecture, we will see more details
about black-body radiation

2
00:00:10,570 --> 00:00:15,360
and the spectral lines produced for example
by an atomic or molecular gas.

3
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:18,820
The black body, first of all, caracterises
heated bodies

4
00:00:18,820 --> 00:00:23,710
that re emit radiation at all wavelengths.
For instance, that is the case of a light

5
00:00:23,710 --> 00:00:27,519
bulb filament that converts
electric energy into light.

6
00:00:27,519 --> 00:00:31,449
That is the case of glowing embers which,
due to the heating by the flames,

7
00:00:31,449 --> 00:00:38,890
will radiate at all wavelengths.
It is also the case of lava ejected by volcanoes.

8
00:00:38,890 --> 00:00:42,289
This blackbody radiation is characterised
by

9
00:00:42,289 --> 00:00:47,630
what we call the Planckian curve
which gives the energy distribution as a function

10
00:00:47,630 --> 00:00:53,690
of wavelength
or as a function of frequency.

11
00:00:53,690 --> 00:00:58,449
The units of this luminance (or specific intensity)
is a power

12
00:00:58,449 --> 00:01:05,210
by surface unit, by steradian,
for radiation that is emitted in all directions

13
00:01:05,210 --> 00:01:10,170
and optionally by wavelength unit as shown
here on that axis,

14
00:01:10,170 --> 00:01:17,270
or by frequency unit.
These Planckian curves have a bell shape

15
00:01:17,270 --> 00:01:21,320
with an increasing and decreasing slope and
so also a maximum.

16
00:01:21,320 --> 00:01:29,939
The position of this maximum can be calculated
by deriving the function which gives the luminance.

17
00:01:29,939 --> 00:01:34,210
If we do it here, as a function of wavelength
we will find that the maximum of the curve

18
00:01:34,210 --> 00:01:39,360
will occur
at a position that depends only upon the temperature.

19
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:44,140
We have therefore a linear relation between
the position of the maximum

20
00:01:44,140 --> 00:01:48,329
of the black body curve and the black body
temperature.

21
00:01:48,329 --> 00:01:54,729
So here we have a constant in m.K.
We can have it in Å.K, which is more useful

22
00:01:54,729 --> 00:01:58,259
with the units we use
in astrophysics, in the wavelength range

23
00:01:58,259 --> 00:02:01,950
used in astrophysics.
We can see here the position of the maximun

24
00:02:01,950 --> 00:02:10,090
of the black body curve
for a black body temperature of 6000K.

25
00:02:10,090 --> 00:02:19,531
Or here for a temperature of 5780K.
That is the surface temperature of the sun

26
00:02:19,531 --> 00:02:25,620
for example.
and these curves show different temperatures,

27
00:02:25,620 --> 00:02:40,379
here 5500K,
5000K and 4500K.

28
00:02:40,379 --> 00:02:46,200
Stars are excellent black bodies.
So we can immediately see that λmax decreases

29
00:02:46,200 --> 00:02:51,080
when T increases.
We can indeed observe it here.

30
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:56,659
A high temperature yields a peak emission
in the short wavelengths, the bluer ones.

31
00:02:56,659 --> 00:03:00,440
And lower temperatures result in emission
peaks

32
00:03:00,440 --> 00:03:04,380
that lie at higher wavelengths, the redder
ones.

33
00:03:04,380 --> 00:03:09,300
Since we have red on this side of the spectrum
and blue on that side,

34
00:03:09,300 --> 00:03:17,659
in the optical wavelengths range
A hot star will appear blue

35
00:03:17,659 --> 00:03:26,019
