105
00:09:51,940 --> 00:09:58,040
in the upper layers of the stellar atmosphere.
Let's see in more details the line spectrum

106
00:09:58,040 --> 00:10:02,310
produced in this case here
by the hydrogen atoms.

107
00:10:02,310 --> 00:10:06,720
For that, let's go back to Bohr's atomic model
where the electron is in orbit around the

108
00:10:06,720 --> 00:10:09,720
proton.
We obviously have an equilibrium between the

109
00:10:09,720 --> 00:10:15,240
Coulomb force.
We have a proton and then an electron in orbit

110
00:10:15,240 --> 00:10:23,800
around the proton,
namely, a hydrogen atom.

111
00:10:23,800 --> 00:10:28,800
This is the mass times acceleration. This
is just the Newtons law here.

112
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:31,670
Quantum mechanics tells us that kinetic momentum
is quantified

113
00:10:31,670 --> 00:10:40,270
and that the kinetic momentum takes an integer
value multiplied by a constant.

114
00:10:40,270 --> 00:10:45,140
Here we have an integer value
times a constant, which is the h bar constant

115
00:10:45,140 --> 00:10:55,030
namely the Planck constant divided by 2π,
so h / 2π.

116
00:10:55,030 --> 00:10:58,840
The two equations which we have written in
the previous slide

117
00:10:58,840 --> 00:11:02,500
are simply Newton's law and the quantification
of kinetic momentum,

118
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:06,630
i.e. the fact that the kinetic momentum of
the electron around the proton

119
00:11:06,630 --> 00:11:11,190
can take only very specific values.
These two equations will permit us to express

120
00:11:11,190 --> 00:11:16,580
the total energy of the electron.
So the kinetic energy here and the potential

121
00:11:16,580 --> 00:11:25,390
energy here,
as a function of n and the Planck constant,

122
00:11:25,390 --> 00:11:29,630
so an integer value and the Planck constant,
rather then as a function of the radius and

123
00:11:29,630 --> 00:11:33,490
the velocity of the electron.
So we have two equations with two unknowns,

124
00:11:33,490 --> 00:11:37,680
the solution is trivial.
We come back to the total energy of the electron,

125
00:11:37,680 --> 00:11:42,350
which will be negative
since the system is bound.

126
00:11:42,350 --> 00:11:45,690
The total energy will depend upon a constant,
is negative

127
00:11:45,690 --> 00:11:51,180
and will depend on the energy level characterised
by n,

128
00:11:51,180 --> 00:11:54,180
which we defined earlier and which is responsible
for

129
00:11:54,180 --> 00:11:59,470
the quantification of the kinetic momentum.
The energy of the electron is quantified.

130
00:11:59,470 --> 00:12:05,180
The total energy will depend
on an integer value and a constant.

131
00:12:05,180 --> 00:12:09,880
We recognise here a lot of physical constants:
the Planck constant divided by 2π,

132
00:12:09,880 --> 00:12:16,950
the mass and charge of the electron
and the electrostatic permittivity constant

133
00:12:16,950 --> 00:12:21,210
of vacuum ε0.
If we express all that in numerical terms

134
00:12:21,210 --> 00:12:27,110
we find that this constant is
2.18 x 10^-18 Joules

135
00:12:27,110 --> 00:12:30,730
It is an energy.
If we convert the result into a more useful

136
00:12:30,730 --> 00:12:33,750
energy unit
for particle physics or astrophysics

137
00:12:33,750 --> 00:12:38,960
or also for atomic physics, we find -13,6
eV.

138
00:12:38,960 --> 00:12:43,029
So for the record, an electron-volt is the
energy acquired by one electron

139
00:12:43,029 --> 00:12:48,210
at rest when it is accelerated by a voltage
difference of 1 Volt.

140
00:12:48,210 --> 00:12:56,600
That is the definition of an electron-volt.
We saw that the total energy is quantified,

141
00:12:56,600 --> 00:13:01,120
so we have an energy that is a function of
the integer value n

142
00:13:01,120 --> 00:13:08,940
and depends on the constant -13,6eV * (1/n²)
where in fact n characterises the orbit on

143
00:13:08,940 --> 00:13:14,310
which moves
an electron around the proton.

144
00:13:14,310 --> 00:13:20,470
We have a proton here and then we have an
electron that might be

145
00:13:20,470 --> 00:13:29,810
on an orbit n1 or on an orbit n2.
The electron will be able to go from one orbit

146
00:13:29,810 --> 00:13:34,050
to another
by gaining or losing energy.

147
00:13:34,050 --> 00:13:41,250
If for example a photon is absorbed by an
atom

148
00:13:41,250 --> 00:13:47,100
the electron will be able to go from the n1
layer to the n2 layer

149
00:13:47,100 --> 00:13:50,570
by gaining energy.
Conversely, we can also have electrons

150
00:13:50,570 --> 00:13:57,470
that are in the n2 layer, an "excited" layer,
and then will go back to the n1 layer.

151
00:13:57,470 --> 00:14:04,279
The atom will lose energy,
by emitting a photon with a certain energy

152
00:14:04,279 --> 00:14:09,160
hν.
What the frequency of this photon will be

153
00:14:09,160 --> 00:14:11,230
?
We can compute it by simply calculationg the

154
00:14:11,230 --> 00:14:14,890
energy difference
between the atomic layers of the hydrogen

155
00:14:14,890 --> 00:14:19,480
atom.
For example, the energy difference between

156
00:14:19,480 --> 00:14:22,800
layers 1 and 2
can be expressed using the equation we have

157
00:14:22,800 --> 00:14:26,880
seen before.
-13,6 times the difference of the numerical

158
00:14:26,880 --> 00:14:36,850
constants here.
So (1/n1² -1/n2²) is of course in electron-volts.

159
00:14:36,850 --> 00:14:39,960
It is also the energy that the photons will
have once emitted

160
00:14:39,960 --> 00:14:46,100
by the hydrogen atoms that will go down
from the layer n2 to n1.

161
00:14:46,100 --> 00:14:49,500
It is also the energy one has to bring to
an hydrogen atom to

162
00:14:49,500 --> 00:14:58,770
raise an electron from layer n1 to layer n2.
We can summarize here in a figure what happens

163
00:14:58,770 --> 00:15:02,550
in a hydrogen atom.
We said that we have multiple possible energy

164
00:15:02,550 --> 00:15:07,410
levels that correspond
each time to an integer value, from 1 to the

