The same is true of planetary nebulae
where the differents gas layers are excited

215
00:19:40,040 --> 00:19:43,791
by the radiation
of the white dwarf star lying at the centre

216
00:19:43,791 --> 00:19:47,990
of the nebula.
And, closer to us, the polar aurorae we can

217
00:19:47,990 --> 00:19:51,230
see
during strong solar activity display also

218
00:19:51,230 --> 00:19:54,090
a line spectrum.
We can see one here from the International

219
00:19:54,090 --> 00:19:57,660
Space Station.
In this case the atoms in the upper layers

220
00:19:57,660 --> 00:20:03,090
of the terrestial atmosphere
are excited by collisions with the protons

221
00:20:03,090 --> 00:20:07,490
and electrons from the Sun
that are captured in the terrestrial magnetic

222
00:20:07,490 --> 00:20:10,990
field.
It is by losing energy through de-excitation

223
00:20:10,990 --> 00:20:15,460
that the atoms emit the polar auroras
which have a magnificent line spectrum.

